  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_280641911" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/280641911" />
    <a title="seak" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1805180-seak"><img alt="seak" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612563220p2/1805180.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/280641911?book_show_action=true">Feb 19, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="seak" class="user" itemprop="url" name="seak" href="/user/show/1805180-seak">seak</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1805180-seak?shelf=on-deck">on-deck</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1805180-seak?shelf=2018">2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer280641911" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7132595619143847404">Of course there will be spoilers for the previous books, just a heads up for ya there.<br/><br/>This marks the halfway point in the Wheel of Time. I&apos;ve finally made it ... halfway. It&apos;s no mean feat, so I&apos;ll take what I can get. This review may seem like a huge nitpick, and that would be right, so I don&apos;t know why I used the term &quot;seem,&quot; but having said that, I really do love this series and I think I&apos;m learning to enjoy the journey and the world instead of plot progression. It&apos;s really an amazing world t</span>
  <span id="freeText7132595619143847404" style="display:none">Of course there will be spoilers for the previous books, just a heads up for ya there.<br /><br />This marks the halfway point in the Wheel of Time. I've finally made it ... halfway. It's no mean feat, so I'll take what I can get. This review may seem like a huge nitpick, and that would be right, so I don't know why I used the term "seem," but having said that, I really do love this series and I think I'm learning to enjoy the journey and the world instead of plot progression. It's really an amazing world that I love being immersed in, so I have to keep reminding myself that the journey is what I bought the ticket for.<br /><br />Having said that (I feel like I've been saying this a lot lately), there are plenty of things to comment on and have fun with despite my immense enjoyment.<br /><br />I was warned about this book and the immense slow down that this series takes and it's not too surprising given the last couple books in the series, but it is still a bit frustrating (but see above!). The whole "bowl of winds" or whatever that's supposed to help the weather just seems like a total time waste. Have them go after forsaken, move forward armageddon, isn't that the reason for the crazy weather? I feel like I'm taking crazy pills. <br /><br />By my very accurate calculations, I'm pretty sure A Crown of Swords takes place in all of about 10 days. TEN DAYS is what 856 pages (mmpb) takes us! Are you kidding me! (please correct me if I'm wrong, I've been trying to google this important question)<br /><br />The next needs a bit of a stronger spoiler warning: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ I'm a bit frustrated that Sammael's "death" wasn't a sure thing, which tells me it's not a sure thing, which makes the whole thing pretty much useless... which frustrates me more.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> And what's with the cover of this book, that's quite the spoiler...<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[since Rand is passed out on his deathbed and Shadar Logoth still hasn't happened so you know it has yet to happen, that seemed like a bad idea on the cover.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />As frustrated as I was with a couple things in this, I have to say that Jordon completely had me on multiple occasions. First, with Perrin, and second with Rand. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Rand's injury by Padan Fain, dang! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Overall, I really am learning to enjoy this series while it goes. I think rereading The Dragon Reborn (book 3) helped me in this process, even though I've had to remind myself over and again. TDR had about 10 pages of Rand so the slow down was already forcing its way in the story.<br /><br />4 out of 5 Stars (Might be my least favorite WOT book, but still high quality WOT stuff I've come to expect)</span>
  <a data-text-id="7132595619143847404" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


